# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: logistic-regression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] In statistics, **deviance** is a goodness-of-fit statistic for a statistical model; it is often used for statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] It is a generalization of the idea of using the sum of squares of residuals (SSR) in ordinary least squares to cases where model-fitting is achieved by maximum likelihood.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] It plays an important role in exponential dispersion models and generalized linear models.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] Deviance can be related to Kullback–Leibler divergence.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] The total deviance $D(\mathbf {y} ,{\hat {\boldsymbol {\mu }}})$ of a model with predictions ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\mu }}}$ of the observation $\mathbf {y}$ is the sum of its unit deviances: ${\textstyle D(\mathbf {y} ,{\hat {\boldsymbol {\mu }}})=\sum _{i}d(y_{i},{\hat {\mu }}_{i})}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] Here ${\hat {\theta }}_{0}$ denotes the fitted values of the parameters in the model *M*0, while ${\hat {\theta }}_{s}$ denotes the fitted parameters for the *saturated model*: both sets of fitted values are implicitly functions of the observations *y*.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] Here, the **saturated model** is a model with a parameter for every observation so that the data are fitted exactly.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] This expression is simply 2 times the log-likelihood ratio of the full model compared to the reduced model.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] The deviance is used to compare two models – in particular in the case of generalized linear models (GLM) where it has a similar role to residual sum of squares from ANOVA in linear models (RSS).
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] Suppose in the framework of the GLM, we have two nested models, *M1* and *M2*.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] In particular, suppose that *M1* contains the parameters in *M2*, and *k* additional parameters.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] Then, under the null hypothesis that *M2* is the true model, the difference between the deviances for the two models follows, based on Wilks' theorem, an approximate chi-squared distribution with *k*-degrees of freedom.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] This can be used for hypothesis testing on the deviance.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] Some usage of the term "deviance" can be confusing.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] However, since the principal use is in the form of the difference of the deviances of two models, this confusion in definition is usually unimportant.
[src:logistic-regression/deviance-statistics] The unit deviance for the Poisson distribution is $d(y,\mu )=2\left(y\log {\frac {y}{\mu }}-y+\mu \right)$ , the unit deviance for the normal distribution with unit variance is given by $d(y,\mu )=\left(y-\mu \right)^{2}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] In statistics, a **logistic model** (or **logit model**) is a statistical model that models the log-odds of an event as a linear combination of one or more independent variables.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] In regression analysis, **logistic regression** (or **logit regression**) estimates the parameters of a logistic model (the coefficients in the linear or non linear combinations).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The corresponding probability of the value labeled "1" can vary between 0 (certainly the value "0") and 1 (certainly the value "1"), hence the labeling; the function that converts log-odds to probability is the logistic function, hence the name.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The unit of measurement for the log-odds scale is called a *logit*, from ***log**istic un**it***, hence the alternative names.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] See § Background and § Definition for formal mathematics, and § Example for a worked example.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Binary variables are widely used in statistics to model the probability of a certain class or event taking place, such as the probability of a team winning, of a patient being healthy, etc.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] (see § Applications), and the logistic model has been the most commonly used model for binary regression since about 1970.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Binary variables can be generalized to categorical variables when there are more than two possible values (e.g. whether an image is of a cat, dog, lion, etc.), and the binary logistic regression generalized to multinomial logistic regression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] If the multiple categories are ordered, one can use the ordinal logistic regression (for example the proportional odds ordinal logistic model).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] See § Extensions for further extensions.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Analogous linear models for binary variables with a different sigmoid function instead of the logistic function (to convert the linear combination to a probability) can also be used, most notably the probit model; see § Alternatives.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The defining characteristic of the logistic model is that increasing one of the independent variables multiplicatively scales the odds of the given outcome at a *constant* rate, with each independent variable having its own parameter; for a binary dependent variable this generalizes the odds ratio.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] More abstractly, the logistic function is the natural parameter for the Bernoulli distribution, and in this sense is the "simplest" way to convert a real number to a probability.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The parameters of a logistic regression are most commonly estimated by maximum-likelihood estimation (MLE).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This does not have a closed-form expression, unlike linear least squares; see § Model fitting.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Logistic regression by MLE plays a similarly basic role for binary or categorical responses as linear regression by ordinary least squares (OLS) plays for scalar responses: it is a simple, well-analyzed baseline model; see § Comparison with linear regression for discussion.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The logistic regression as a general statistical model was originally developed and popularized primarily by Joseph Berkson, beginning in Berkson (1944), where he coined "logit"; see § History.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Logistic regression is used in various fields, including machine learning, most medical fields, and social sciences.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] For example, the Trauma and Injury Severity Score (TRISS), which is widely used to predict mortality in injured patients, was originally developed by Boyd *et al.* using logistic regression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Many other medical scales used to assess severity of a patient have been developed using logistic regression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Logistic regression may be used to predict the risk of developing a given disease (e.g. diabetes; coronary heart disease), based on observed characteristics of the patient (age, sex, body mass index, results of various blood tests, etc.).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Another example might be to predict whether a Nepalese voter will vote Nepali Congress or Communist Party of Nepal or for any other party, based on age, income, sex, race, state of residence, votes in previous elections, etc.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The technique can also be used in engineering, especially for predicting the probability of failure of a given process, system or product.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] It is also used in marketing applications such as prediction of a customer's propensity to purchase a product or halt a subscription, etc.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] In economics, it can be used to predict the likelihood of a person ending up in the labor force, and a business application would be to predict the likelihood of a homeowner defaulting on a mortgage.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Conditional random fields, an extension of logistic regression to sequential data, are used in natural language processing.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Disaster planners and engineers rely on these models to predict decisions taken by householders or building occupants in small-scale and large-scales evacuations, such as building fires, wildfires, hurricanes among others.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] These models help in the development of reliable disaster managing plans and safer design for the built environment.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Logistic regression is a supervised machine learning algorithm widely used for binary classification tasks, such as identifying whether an email is spam or not and diagnosing diseases by assessing the presence or absence of specific conditions based on patient test results.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This approach utilizes the logistic (or sigmoid) function to transform a linear combination of input features into a probability value ranging between 0 and 1.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This probability indicates the likelihood that a given input corresponds to one of two predefined categories.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The essential mechanism of logistic regression is grounded in the logistic function's ability to model the probability of binary outcomes accurately.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] With its distinctive S-shaped curve, the logistic function effectively maps any real-valued number to a value within the 0 to 1 interval.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This feature renders it particularly suitable for binary classification tasks, such as sorting emails into "spam" or "not spam".
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] By calculating the probability that the dependent variable will be categorized into a specific group, logistic regression provides a probabilistic framework that supports informed decision-making.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The reason for using logistic regression for this problem is that the values of the dependent variable, pass and fail, while represented by "1" and "0", are not cardinal numbers.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] If the problem was changed so that pass/fail was replaced with the grade 0–100 (cardinal numbers), then simple regression analysis could be used.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The table shows the number of hours each student spent studying, and whether they passed (1) or failed (0).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] We wish to fit a logistic function to the data consisting of the hours studied (*xk*) and the outcome of the test (*yk* =1 for pass, 0 for fail).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The data points are indexed by the subscript *k* which runs from $k=1$ to $k=K=20$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The *x* variable is called the "explanatory variable", and the *y* variable is called the "categorical variable" consisting of two categories: "pass" or "fail" corresponding to the categorical values 1 and 0 respectively.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] where *μ* is a location parameter (the midpoint of the curve, where $p(\mu )=1/2$ ) and *s* is a scale parameter.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] where $\beta _{0}=-\mu /s$ and is known as the intercept (it is the *vertical* intercept or *y*-intercept of the line $y=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x$ ), and $\beta _{1}=1/s$ (inverse scale parameter or rate parameter): these are the *y*-intercept and slope of the log-odds as a function of *x*.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Note that this model is actually an oversimplification, as it implies that every student will pass if they study indefinitely (limit = 1).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The usual measure of goodness of fit for a logistic regression uses logistic loss (or log loss), the negative log-likelihood.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The ⁠ $p_{k}$ ⁠ are the probabilities that the corresponding ⁠ $y_{k}$ ⁠ will equal one, and ⁠ $1-p_{k}$ ⁠ are the probabilities that they will be zero (see Bernoulli distribution).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] We wish to find the values of ⁠ $\beta _{0}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\beta _{1}$ ⁠ which give the "best fit" to the data.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] For comparison of a "best fit" to the data, see the case of linear regression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] There, the sum of the squared deviations of the fit from the data points (*yk*), the squared error loss, is taken as a measure of the goodness of fit, and the best fit is obtained when this loss is *minimized*.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The log loss can be interpreted as the "surprisal" of the actual outcome ⁠ $y_{k}$ ⁠ relative to the prediction ⁠ $p_{k}$ ⁠, and is a measure of information content.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Since the value of the logistic function is always strictly between zero and one, the log loss is always greater than zero and less than infinity.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Unlike in a linear regression, where the model can have zero loss at a point by passing through a data point (and zero loss overall if all points are on a line), in a logistic regression it is not possible to have zero loss at any points, since ⁠ $y_{k}$ ⁠ is either 0 or 1, but ⁠ $0<p_{k}<1$ ⁠.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This expression is more formally known as the cross-entropy of the predicted distribution ${\big (}p_{k},(1-p_{k}){\big )}$ from the actual distribution ${\big (}y_{k},(1-y_{k}){\big )}$ , as probability distributions on the two-element space of (pass, fail).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The sum of these, the total loss, is the overall negative log-likelihood ⁠ $-\ell$ ⁠, and the best fit is obtained for those choices of ⁠ $\beta _{0}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\beta _{1}$ ⁠ for which ⁠ $-\ell$ ⁠ is *minimized*.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This method is known as maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Since *ℓ* is nonlinear in ⁠ $\beta _{0}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\beta _{1}$ ⁠, determining their optimum values will require numerical methods.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] and the maximization procedure can be accomplished by solving the above two equations for ⁠ $\beta _{0}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\beta _{1}$ ⁠, which, again, will generally require the use of numerical methods.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The ⁠ $\beta _{0}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\beta _{1}$ ⁠ coefficients may be entered into the logistic regression equation to estimate the probability of passing the exam.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This table shows the estimated probability of passing the exam for several values of hours studying.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The logistic regression analysis gives the following output.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] By the Wald test, the output indicates that hours studying is significantly associated with the probability of passing the exam ( $p=0.017$ ).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Rather than the Wald method, the recommended method to calculate the *p*-value for logistic regression is the likelihood-ratio test (LRT), which for these data give $p\approx 0.00064$ (see § Deviance and likelihood ratio tests below).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This simple model is an example of binary logistic regression, and has one explanatory variable and a binary categorical variable which can assume one of two categorical values.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Multinomial logistic regression is the generalization of binary logistic regression to include any number of explanatory variables and any number of categories.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] An explanation of logistic regression can begin with an explanation of the standard logistic function.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The logistic function is a sigmoid function, which takes any real input t , and outputs a value between zero and one.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] For the logit, this is interpreted as taking input log-odds and having output probability.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] A graph of the logistic function on the *t*-interval (−6,6) is shown in Figure 1.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Let us assume that t is a linear function of a single explanatory variable x (the case where t is a *linear combination* of multiple explanatory variables is treated similarly).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] In the logistic model, $p(x)$ is interpreted as the probability of the dependent variable Y equaling a success/case rather than a failure/non-case.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] It is clear that the response variables $Y_{i}$ are not identically distributed: $P(Y_{i}=1\mid X)$ differs from one data point $X_{i}$ to another, though they are independent given design matrix X and shared parameters $\beta$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] We can now define the logit (log odds) function as the inverse $g=\sigma ^{-1}$ of the standard logistic function.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The odds of the dependent variable equaling a case (given some linear combination x of the predictors) is equivalent to the exponential function of the linear regression expression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This illustrates how the logit serves as a link function between the probability and the linear regression expression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Given that the logit ranges between negative and positive infinity, it provides an adequate criterion upon which to conduct linear regression and the logit is easily converted back into the odds.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This exponential relationship provides an interpretation for $\beta _{1}$ : The odds multiply by $e^{\beta _{1}}$ for every 1-unit increase in x.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] For a binary independent variable the odds ratio is defined as ${\frac {ad}{bc}}$ where *a*, *b*, *c* and *d* are cells in a 2×2 contingency table.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Then when this is used in the equation relating the log odds of a success to the values of the predictors, the linear regression will be a multiple regression with *m* explanators; the parameters $\beta _{i}$ for all $i=0,1,2,\dots ,m$ are all estimated.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Each point *i* consists of a set of *m* input variables *x*1,*i* ...
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The goal of logistic regression is to use the dataset to create a predictive model of the outcome variable.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] As in linear regression, the outcome variables *Y**i* are assumed to depend on the explanatory variables *x*1,*i* ...
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The explanatory variables may be of any type: real-valued, binary, categorical, etc.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The main distinction is between continuous variables and discrete variables.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Formally, the outcomes *Y**i* are described as being Bernoulli-distributed data, where each outcome is determined by an unobserved probability *p**i* that is specific to the outcome at hand, but related to the explanatory variables.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The second line expresses the fact that the expected value of each *Y**i* is equal to the probability of success *p**i*, which is a general property of the Bernoulli distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] In other words, if we run a large number of Bernoulli trials using the same probability of success *p**i*, then take the average of all the 1 and 0 outcomes, then the result would be close to *p**i*.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This is because doing an average this way simply computes the proportion of successes seen, which we expect to converge to the underlying probability of success.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The third line writes out the probability mass function of the Bernoulli distribution, specifying the probability of seeing each of the two possible outcomes.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The fourth line is another way of writing the probability mass function, which avoids having to write separate cases and is more convenient for certain types of calculations.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] This relies on the fact that *Y**i* can take only the value 0 or 1.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] In each case, one of the exponents will be 1, "choosing" the value under it, while the other is 0, "canceling out" the value under it.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Hence, the outcome is either *p**i* or 1 − *p**i*, as in the previous line.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] where $\beta _{0},\ldots ,\beta _{m}$ are regression coefficients indicating the relative effect of a particular explanatory variable on the outcome.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] using the notation for a dot product between two vectors.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The above example of binary logistic regression on one explanatory variable can be generalized to binary logistic regression on any number of explanatory variables *x1, x2,...* and any number of categorical values $y=0,1,2,\dots$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] To begin with, we may consider a logistic model with *M* explanatory variables, *x1*, *x2* ...
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] *xM* and, as in the example above, two categorical values (*y* = 0 and 1).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] For the simple binary logistic regression model, we assumed a linear relationship between the predictor variable and the log-odds (also called logit) of the event that $y=1$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] where *t* is the log-odds and $\beta _{i}$ are parameters of the model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] An additional generalization has been introduced in which the base of the model (*b*) is not restricted to Euler's number *e*.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] In most applications, the base b of the logarithm is usually taken to be *e*.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] However, in some cases it can be easier to communicate results by working in base 2 or base 10.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] with an added explanatory variable *x0* =1.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] where $S_{b}$ is the sigmoid function with base b .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The above formula shows that once the $\beta _{m}$ are fixed, we can easily compute either the log-odds that $y=1$ for a given observation, or the probability that $y=1$ for a given observation.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The main use-case of a logistic model is to be given an observation ${\boldsymbol {x}}$ , and estimate the probability $p({\boldsymbol {x}})$ that $y=1$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The optimum beta coefficients may again be found by maximizing the log-likelihood.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] As in the simple example above, finding the optimum *β* parameters will require numerical methods.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] where *xmk* is the value of the *xm* explanatory variable from the *k-th* measurement.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Consider an example with $M=2$ explanatory variables, $b=10$ , and coefficients $\beta _{0}=-3$ , $\beta _{1}=1$ , and $\beta _{2}=2$ which have been determined by the above method.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] where *p* is the probability of the event that $y=1$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The sum of these probabilities equals 1, which must be true, since "0" and "1" are the only possible categories in this setup.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The sum of these probabilities over all categories must equal 1.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Each of the probabilities except $p_{0}({\boldsymbol {x}})$ will have their own set of regression coefficients ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{n}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] It can be seen that, as required, the sum of the $p_{n}({\boldsymbol {x}})$ over all categories *n* is 1.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The selection of $p_{0}({\boldsymbol {x}})$ to be defined in terms of the other probabilities is artificial.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Any of the probabilities could have been selected to be so defined.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] The log-likelihood that a particular set of *K* measurements or data points will be generated by the above probabilities can now be calculated.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Indexing each measurement by *k*, let the *k*-th set of measured explanatory variables be denoted by ${\boldsymbol {x}}_{k}$ and their categorical outcomes be denoted by $y_{k}$ which can be equal to any integer in [0,N].
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] where $\Delta (n,y_{k})$ is an indicator function which equals 1 if *yk = n* and zero otherwise.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] In the case of two explanatory variables, this indicator function was defined as *yk* when *n* = 1 and *1-yk* when *n* = 0.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Again, the optimum beta coefficients may be found by maximizing the log-likelihood function generally using numerical methods.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] where $\beta _{nm}$ is the *m*-th coefficient of the ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{n}$ vector and $x_{mk}$ is the *m*-th explanatory variable of the *k*-th measurement.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p01] Once the beta coefficients have been estimated from the data, we will be able to estimate the probability that any subsequent set of explanatory variables will result in any of the possible outcome categories.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] There are various equivalent specifications and interpretations of logistic regression, which fit into different types of more general models, and allow different generalizations.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This formulation expresses logistic regression as a type of generalized linear model, which predicts variables with various types of probability distributions by fitting a linear predictor function of the above form to some sort of arbitrary transformation of the expected value of the variable.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The intuition for transforming using the logit function (the natural log of the odds) was explained above.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] It also has the practical effect of converting the probability (which is bounded to be between 0 and 1) to a variable that ranges over $(-\infty ,+\infty )$ — thereby matching the potential range of the linear prediction function on the right side of the equation.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Both the probabilities *p**i* and the regression coefficients are unobserved, and the means of determining them is not part of the model itself.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The use of a regularization condition is equivalent to doing maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimation, an extension of maximum likelihood.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The interpretation of the *β**j* parameter estimates is as the additive effect on the log of the odds for a unit change in the *j* the explanatory variable.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In the case of a dichotomous explanatory variable, for instance, gender $e^{\beta }$ is the estimate of the odds of having the outcome for, say, males compared with females.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The logistic model has an equivalent formulation as a latent-variable model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This formulation is common in the theory of discrete choice models and makes it easier to extend to certain more complicated models with multiple, correlated choices, as well as to compare logistic regression to the closely related probit model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] i.e. the latent variable can be written directly in terms of the linear predictor function and an additive random error variable that is distributed according to a standard logistic distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The choice of modeling the error variable specifically with a standard logistic distribution, rather than a general logistic distribution with the location and scale set to arbitrary values, seems restrictive, but in fact, it is not.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] It must be kept in mind that we can choose the regression coefficients ourselves, and very often can use them to offset changes in the parameters of the error variable's distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] For example, a logistic error-variable distribution with a non-zero location parameter *μ* (which sets the mean) is equivalent to a distribution with a zero location parameter, where *μ* has been added to the intercept coefficient.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Both situations produce the same value for *Y**i** regardless of settings of explanatory variables.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Similarly, an arbitrary scale parameter *s* is equivalent to setting the scale parameter to 1 and then dividing all regression coefficients by *s*.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In the latter case, the resulting value of *Y**i**** will be smaller by a factor of *s* than in the former case, for all sets of explanatory variables — but critically, it will always remain on the same side of 0, and hence lead to the same *Y**i* choice.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] It turns out that this formulation is exactly equivalent to the preceding one, phrased in terms of the generalized linear model and without any latent variables.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This can be shown as follows, using the fact that the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of the standard logistic distribution is the logistic function, which is the inverse of the logit function, i.e.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This formulation—which is standard in discrete choice models—makes clear the relationship between logistic regression (the "logit model") and the probit model, which uses an error variable distributed according to a standard normal distribution instead of a standard logistic distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Both the logistic and normal distributions are symmetric with a basic unimodal, "bell curve" shape.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The only difference is that the logistic distribution has somewhat heavier tails, which means that it is less sensitive to outlying data (and hence somewhat more robust to model mis-specifications or erroneous data).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] where *EV*1(0,1) is a standard type-1 extreme value distribution: i.e.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This model has a separate latent variable and a separate set of regression coefficients for each possible outcome of the dependent variable.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The reason for this separation is that it makes it easy to extend logistic regression to multi-outcome categorical variables, as in the multinomial logit model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In such a model, it is natural to model each possible outcome using a different set of regression coefficients.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] It is also possible to motivate each of the separate latent variables as the theoretical utility associated with making the associated choice, and thus motivate logistic regression in terms of utility theory.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The choice of the type-1 extreme value distribution seems fairly arbitrary, but it makes the mathematics work out, and it may be possible to justify its use through rational choice theory.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] It turns out that this model is equivalent to the previous model, although this seems non-obvious, since there are now two sets of regression coefficients and error variables, and the error variables have a different distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] An intuition for this comes from the fact that, since we choose based on the maximum of two values, only their difference matters, not the exact values — and this effectively removes one degree of freedom.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Yet another formulation combines the two-way latent variable formulation above with the original formulation higher up without latent variables, and in the process provides a link to one of the standard formulations of the multinomial logit.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Two separate sets of regression coefficients have been introduced, just as in the two-way latent variable model, and the two equations appear a form that writes the logarithm of the associated probability as a linear predictor, with an extra term $-\ln Z$ at the end.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This term, as it turns out, serves as the normalizing factor ensuring that the result is a distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In this form it is clear that the purpose of *Z* is to ensure that the resulting distribution over *Y**i* is in fact a probability distribution, i.e. it sums to 1.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This means that *Z* is simply the sum of all un-normalized probabilities, and by dividing each probability by *Z*, the probabilities become "normalized".
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This shows clearly how to generalize this formulation to more than two outcomes, as in multinomial logit.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] To prove that this is equivalent to the previous model, we start by recognizing the above model is overspecified, in that $\Pr(Y_{i}=0)$ and $\Pr(Y_{i}=1)$ cannot be independently specified: rather $\Pr(Y_{i}=0)+\Pr(Y_{i}=1)=1$ so knowing one automatically determines the other.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] As a result, the model is nonidentifiable, in that multiple combinations of ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{0}$ and ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{1}$ will produce the same probabilities for all possible explanatory variables.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] As a result, we can simplify matters, and restore identifiability, by picking an arbitrary value for one of the two vectors.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] which shows that this formulation is indeed equivalent to the previous formulation.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Most treatments of the multinomial logit model start out either by extending the "log-linear" formulation presented here or the two-way latent variable formulation presented above, since both clearly show the way that the model could be extended to multi-way outcomes.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In general, the presentation with latent variables is more common in econometrics and political science, where discrete choice models and utility theory reign, while the "log-linear" formulation here is more common in computer science, e.g. machine learning and natural language processing.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This functional form is commonly called a single-layer perceptron or single-layer artificial neural network.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] A single-layer neural network computes a continuous output instead of a step function.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] where *f*(*X*) is an analytic function in *X*.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] With this choice, the single-layer neural network is identical to the logistic regression model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This function has a continuous derivative, which allows it to be used in backpropagation.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] An example of this distribution is the fraction of seeds (*p**i*) that germinate after *n**i* are planted.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This model can be fit using the same sorts of methods as the above more basic model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The regression coefficients are usually estimated using maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Unlike linear regression with normally distributed residuals, it is not possible to find a closed-form expression for the coefficient values that maximize the likelihood function so an iterative process must be used instead; for example Newton's method.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This process begins with a tentative solution, revises it slightly to see if it can be improved, and repeats this revision until no more improvement is made, at which point the process is said to have converged.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In some instances, the model may not reach convergence.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Non-convergence of a model indicates that the coefficients are not meaningful because the iterative process was unable to find appropriate solutions.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] A failure to converge may occur for a number of reasons: having a large ratio of predictors to cases, multicollinearity, sparseness, or complete separation.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Binary logistic regression ( $y=0$ or $y=1$ ) can, for example, be calculated using *iteratively reweighted least squares* (IRLS), which is equivalent to maximizing the log-likelihood of a Bernoulli distributed process using Newton's method.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] the regressor matrix and $\mathbf {y} (i)=[y(1),y(2),\ldots ]^{T}$ the vector of response variables.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] More details can be found in the literature.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In a Bayesian statistics context, prior distributions are normally placed on the regression coefficients, for example in the form of Gaussian distributions.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] There is no conjugate prior of the likelihood function in logistic regression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] When Bayesian inference was performed analytically, this made the posterior distribution difficult to calculate except in very low dimensions.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Now, though, automatic software such as OpenBUGS, JAGS, PyMC, Stan or Turing.jl allows these posteriors to be computed using simulation, so lack of conjugacy is not a concern.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] However, when the sample size or the number of parameters is large, full Bayesian simulation can be slow, and people often use approximate methods such as variational Bayesian methods and expectation propagation.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Widely used, the "one in ten rule", states that logistic regression models give stable values for the explanatory variables if based on a minimum of about 10 events per explanatory variable (EPV); where *event* denotes the cases belonging to the less frequent category in the dependent variable.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Thus a study designed to use k explanatory variables for an event (e.g. myocardial infarction) expected to occur in a proportion p of participants in the study will require a total of $10k/p$ participants.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] However, there is considerable debate about the reliability of this rule, which is based on simulation studies and lacks a secure theoretical underpinning.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The worst instances of each problem were not severe with 5–9 EPV and usually comparable to those with 10–16 EPV".
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Others have found results that are not consistent with the above, using different criteria.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] A useful criterion is whether the fitted model will be expected to achieve the same predictive discrimination in a new sample as it appeared to achieve in the model development sample.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] For that criterion, 20 events per candidate variable may be required.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Also, one can argue that 96 observations are needed only to estimate the model's intercept precisely enough that the margin of error in predicted probabilities is ±0.1 with a 0.95 confidence level.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In any fitting procedure, the addition of another fitting parameter to a model (e.g. the beta parameters in a logistic regression model) will almost always improve the ability of the model to predict the measured outcomes.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This will be true even if the additional term has no predictive value, since the model will simply be "overfitting" to the noise in the data.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The question arises as to whether the improvement gained by the addition of another fitting parameter is significant enough to recommend the inclusion of the additional term, or whether the improvement is simply that which may be expected from overfitting.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In short, for logistic regression, a statistic known as the deviance is defined which is a measure of the error between the logistic model fit and the outcome data.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In the limit of a large number of data points, the deviance is chi-squared distributed, which allows a chi-squared test to be implemented in order to determine the significance of the explanatory variables.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Linear regression and logistic regression have many similarities.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] For example, in simple linear regression, a set of *K* data points (*xk*, *yk*) are fitted to a proposed model function of the form $y=b_{0}+b_{1}x$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The fitting process consists of choosing a value of *b*0 which minimizes $\varepsilon ^{2}$ of the fit to the null model, denoted by $\varepsilon _{\varphi }^{2}$ where the $\varphi$ subscript denotes the null model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] which is proportional to the square of the (uncorrected) sample standard deviation of the *yk* data points.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] We can imagine a case where the *yk* data points are randomly assigned to the various *xk*, and then fitted using the proposed model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Specifically, we can consider the fits of the proposed model to every permutation of the *yk* outcomes.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] For logistic regression, the measure of goodness-of-fit is the likelihood function *L*, or its logarithm, the log-likelihood *ℓ*.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The likelihood function *L* is analogous to the $\varepsilon ^{2}$ in the linear regression case, except that the likelihood is maximized rather than minimized.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Denote the maximized log-likelihood of the proposed model by ${\hat {\ell }}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] where ⁠ $p(x)$ ⁠ is the probability that $y=1$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] where ${\overline {y}}$ is again the mean of the *yk* values.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Using the chi-squared test of significance, the integral of the chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom from 11.6661... to infinity is equal to 0.00063649...
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This effectively means that about 6 out of a 10,000 fits to random *yk* can be expected to have a better fit (smaller deviance) than the given *yk* and so we can conclude that the inclusion of the *x* variable and data in the proposed model is a very significant improvement over the null model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In other words, we reject the null hypothesis with $1-D\approx 99.94\%$ confidence.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Goodness of fit in linear regression models is generally measured using R2.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Since this has no direct analog in logistic regression, various methods including the following can be used instead.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In linear regression analysis, one is concerned with partitioning variance via the sum of squares calculations – variance in the criterion is essentially divided into variance accounted for by the predictors and residual variance.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In logistic regression analysis, deviance is used in lieu of a sum of squares calculations.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Deviance is analogous to the sum of squares calculations in linear regression and is a measure of the lack of fit to the data in a logistic regression model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] When a "saturated" model is available (a model with a theoretically perfect fit), deviance is calculated by comparing a given model with the saturated model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In the above equation, D represents the deviance and ln represents the natural logarithm.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The log of this likelihood ratio (the ratio of the fitted model to the saturated model) will produce a negative value, hence the need for a negative sign.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] D can be shown to follow an approximate chi-squared distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Smaller values indicate better fit as the fitted model deviates less from the saturated model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] When assessed upon a chi-square distribution, nonsignificant chi-square values indicate very little unexplained variance and thus, good model fit.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Conversely, a significant chi-square value indicates that a significant amount of the variance is unexplained.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] When the saturated model is not available (a common case), deviance is calculated simply as −2·(log likelihood of the fitted model), and the reference to the saturated model's log likelihood can be removed from all that follows without harm.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Two measures of deviance are particularly important in logistic regression: null deviance and model deviance.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The null deviance represents the difference between a model with only the intercept (which means "no predictors") and the saturated model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The model deviance represents the difference between a model with at least one predictor and the saturated model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In this respect, the null model provides a baseline upon which to compare predictor models.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Given that deviance is a measure of the difference between a given model and the saturated model, smaller values indicate better fit.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Thus, to assess the contribution of a predictor or set of predictors, one can subtract the model deviance from the null deviance and assess the difference on a $\chi _{s-p}^{2},$ chi-square distribution with degrees of freedom equal to the difference in the number of parameters estimated.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] If the model deviance is significantly smaller than the null deviance then one can conclude that the predictor or set of predictors significantly improve the model's fit.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This is analogous to the F-test used in linear regression analysis to assess the significance of prediction.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In linear regression the squared multiple correlation, R2 is used to assess goodness of fit as it represents the proportion of variance in the criterion that is explained by the predictors.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In logistic regression analysis, there is no agreed upon analogous measure, but there are several competing measures each with limitations.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The Hosmer–Lemeshow test uses a test statistic that asymptotically follows a $\chi ^{2}$ distribution to assess whether or not the observed event rates match expected event rates in subgroups of the model population.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This test is considered to be obsolete by some statisticians because of its dependence on arbitrary binning of predicted probabilities and relative low power.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] After fitting the model, it is likely that researchers will want to examine the contribution of individual predictors.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] To do so, they will want to examine the regression coefficients.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In linear regression, the regression coefficients represent the change in the criterion for each unit change in the predictor.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In logistic regression, however, the regression coefficients represent the change in the logit for each unit change in the predictor.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Given that the logit is not intuitive, researchers are likely to focus on a predictor's effect on the exponential function of the regression coefficient – the odds ratio (see definition).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In linear regression, the significance of a regression coefficient is assessed by computing a *t* test.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In logistic regression, there are several different tests designed to assess the significance of an individual predictor, most notably the likelihood ratio test and the Wald statistic.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The likelihood-ratio test discussed above to assess model fit is also the recommended procedure to assess the contribution of individual "predictors" to a given model.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In the case of a single predictor model, one simply compares the deviance of the predictor model with that of the null model on a chi-square distribution with a single degree of freedom.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] If the predictor model has significantly smaller deviance (c.f. chi-square using the difference in degrees of freedom of the two models), then one can conclude that there is a significant association between the "predictor" and the outcome.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Although some common statistical packages (e.g.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] SPSS) do provide likelihood ratio test statistics, without this computationally intensive test it would be more difficult to assess the contribution of individual predictors in the multiple logistic regression case.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] To assess the contribution of individual predictors one can enter the predictors hierarchically, comparing each new model with the previous to determine the contribution of each predictor.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] There is some debate among statisticians about the appropriateness of so-called "stepwise" procedures.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The fear is that they may not preserve nominal statistical properties and may become misleading.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Alternatively, when assessing the contribution of individual predictors in a given model, one may examine the significance of the Wald statistic.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The Wald statistic, analogous to the *t*-test in linear regression, is used to assess the significance of coefficients.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The Wald statistic is the ratio of the square of the regression coefficient to the square of the standard error of the coefficient and is asymptotically distributed as a chi-square distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Although several statistical packages (e.g., SPSS, SAS) report the Wald statistic to assess the contribution of individual predictors, the Wald statistic has limitations.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] When the regression coefficient is large, the standard error of the regression coefficient also tends to be larger increasing the probability of Type-II error.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The Wald statistic also tends to be biased when data are sparse.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Then we might wish to sample them more frequently than their prevalence in the population.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] For example, suppose there is a disease that affects 1 person in 10,000 and to collect our data we need to do a complete physical.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] It may be too expensive to do thousands of physicals of healthy people in order to obtain data for only a few diseased individuals.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Thus, we may evaluate more diseased individuals, perhaps all of the rare outcomes.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This is also retrospective sampling, or equivalently it is called unbalanced data.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] As a rule of thumb, sampling controls at a rate of five times the number of cases will produce sufficient control data.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Logistic regression is unique in that it may be estimated on unbalanced data, rather than randomly sampled data, and still yield correct coefficient estimates of the effects of each independent variable on the outcome.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] That is to say, if we form a logistic model from such data, if the model is correct in the general population, the $\beta _{j}$ parameters are all correct except for $\beta _{0}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] where $\pi$ is the true prevalence and ${\tilde {\pi }}$ is the prevalence in the sample.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Like other forms of regression analysis, logistic regression makes use of one or more predictor variables that may be either continuous or categorical.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Unlike ordinary linear regression, however, logistic regression is used for predicting dependent variables that take membership in one of a limited number of categories (treating the dependent variable in the binomial case as the outcome of a Bernoulli trial) rather than a continuous outcome.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Given this difference, the assumptions of linear regression are violated.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In particular, the residuals cannot be normally distributed.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In addition, linear regression may make nonsensical predictions for a binary dependent variable.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] What is needed is a way to convert a binary variable into a continuous one that can take on any real value (negative or positive).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] To do that, binomial logistic regression first calculates the odds of the event happening for different levels of each independent variable, and then takes its logarithm to create a continuous criterion as a transformed version of the dependent variable.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Although the dependent variable in logistic regression is Bernoulli, the logit is on an unrestricted scale.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Y is the Bernoulli-distributed response variable and x is the predictor variable; the β values are the linear parameters.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The logit of the probability of success is then fitted to the predictors.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The predicted value of the logit is converted back into predicted odds, via the inverse of the natural logarithm – the exponential function.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Thus, although the observed dependent variable in binary logistic regression is a 0-or-1 variable, the logistic regression estimates the odds, as a continuous variable, that the dependent variable is a 'success'.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In some applications, the odds are all that is needed.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In others, a specific yes-or-no prediction is needed for whether the dependent variable is or is not a 'success'; this categorical prediction can be based on the computed odds of success, with predicted odds above some chosen cutoff value being translated into a prediction of success.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] In machine learning applications where logistic regression is used for binary classification, the MLE minimises the cross-entropy loss function.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Logistic regression is an important machine learning algorithm.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] The goal is to model the probability of a random variable Y being 0 or 1 given experimental data.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] which is maximized using optimization techniques such as gradient descent.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] where $H(Y\mid X)$ is the conditional entropy and $D_{\text{KL}}$ is the Kullback–Leibler divergence.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] This leads to the intuition that by maximizing the log-likelihood of a model, you are minimizing the KL divergence of your model from the maximal entropy distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p02] Intuitively searching for the model that makes the fewest assumptions in its parameters.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] Logistic regression can be seen as a special case of the generalized linear model and thus analogous to linear regression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The model of logistic regression, however, is based on quite different assumptions (about the relationship between the dependent and independent variables) from those of linear regression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] In particular, the key differences between these two models can be seen in the following two features of logistic regression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] First, the conditional distribution $y\mid x$ is a Bernoulli distribution rather than a Gaussian distribution, because the dependent variable is binary.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] Second, the predicted values are probabilities and are therefore restricted to (0,1) through the logistic distribution function because logistic regression predicts the **probability** of particular outcomes rather than the outcomes themselves.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] A common alternative to the logistic model (logit model) is the probit model, as the related names suggest.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] From the perspective of generalized linear models, these differ in the choice of link function: the logistic model uses the logit function (inverse logistic function), while the probit model uses the probit function (inverse error function).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] Equivalently, in the latent variable interpretations of these two methods, the first assumes a standard logistic distribution of errors and the second a standard normal distribution of errors.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] Other sigmoid functions or error distributions can be used instead.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] Logistic regression is an alternative to Fisher's 1936 method, linear discriminant analysis.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] If the assumptions of linear discriminant analysis hold, the conditioning can be reversed to produce logistic regression.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The converse is not true, however, because logistic regression does not require the multivariate normal assumption of discriminant analysis.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The assumption of linear predictor effects can easily be relaxed using techniques such as spline functions.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] A detailed history of the logistic regression is given in Cramer (2002).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The logistic function was developed as a model of population growth and named "logistic" by Pierre François Verhulst in the 1830s and 1840s, under the guidance of Adolphe Quetelet; see Logistic function § History for details.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] In his earliest paper (1838), Verhulst did not specify how he fit the curves to the data.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] In his more detailed paper (1845), Verhulst determined the three parameters of the model by making the curve pass through three observed points, which yielded poor predictions.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The logistic function was independently developed in chemistry as a model of autocatalysis (Wilhelm Ostwald, 1883).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] An autocatalytic reaction is one in which one of the products is itself a catalyst for the same reaction, while the supply of one of the reactants is fixed.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] This naturally gives rise to the logistic equation for the same reason as population growth: the reaction is self-reinforcing but constrained.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The logistic function was independently rediscovered as a model of population growth in 1920 by Raymond Pearl and Lowell Reed, published as Pearl & Reed (1920), which led to its use in modern statistics.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] They were initially unaware of Verhulst's work and presumably learned about it from L.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] Gustave du Pasquier, but they gave him little credit and did not adopt his terminology.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] Verhulst's priority was acknowledged and the term "logistic" revived by Udny Yule in 1925 and has been followed since.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] Pearl and Reed first applied the model to the population of the United States, and also initially fitted the curve by making it pass through three points; as with Verhulst, this again yielded poor results.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] In the 1930s, the probit model was developed and systematized by Chester Ittner Bliss, who coined the term "probit" in Bliss (1934), and by John Gaddum in Gaddum (1933), and the model fit by maximum likelihood estimation by Ronald A.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] Fisher in Fisher (1935), as an addendum to Bliss's work.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The probit model was principally used in bioassay, and had been preceded by earlier work dating to 1860; see Probit model § History.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The probit model influenced the subsequent development of the logit model and these models competed with each other.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The logistic model was likely first used as an alternative to the probit model in bioassay by Edwin Bidwell Wilson and his student Jane Worcester in Wilson & Worcester (1943).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] However, the development of the logistic model as a general alternative to the probit model was principally due to the work of Joseph Berkson over many decades, beginning in Berkson (1944), where he coined "logit", by analogy with "probit", and continuing through Berkson (1951) and following years.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The logit model was initially dismissed as inferior to the probit model, but "gradually achieved an equal footing with the probit", particularly between 1960 and 1970.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] By 1970, the logit model achieved parity with the probit model in use in statistics journals and thereafter surpassed it.
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] Various refinements occurred during that time, notably by David Cox, as in Cox (1958).
[src:logistic-regression/logistic-regression-p03] The multinomial logit model was introduced independently in Cox (1966) and Theil (1969), which greatly increased the scope of application and the popularity of the logit model.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] In statistics, the **logit** (/ˈloʊdʒɪt/ *LOH-jit*) function is the quantile function associated with the standard logistic distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] It has many uses in data analysis and machine learning, especially in data transformations.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] Because of this, the logit is also called the **log-odds** since it is equal to the logarithm of the odds ${\textstyle {\frac {p}{1-p}}}$ where p is a probability.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] Thus, the logit is a type of function that maps probability values from $(0,1)$ to real numbers in ⁠ $(-\infty ,+\infty )$ ⁠, akin to the probit function.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] The base of the logarithm function used is of little importance in the present article, as long as it is greater than 1, but the natural logarithm with base e is the one most often used.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] The choice of base corresponds to the choice of logarithmic unit for the value: base 2 corresponds to a shannon, base e to a nat, and base 10 to a hartley; these units are particularly used in information-theoretic interpretations.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] For each choice of base, the logit function takes values between negative and positive infinity.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] Several approaches have been explored to adapt linear regression methods to a domain where the output is a probability value ⁠ $(0,1)$ ⁠, instead of any real number ⁠ $(-\infty ,+\infty )$ ⁠.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] In many cases, such efforts have focused on modeling this problem by mapping the range ⁠ $(0,1)$ ⁠ to ⁠ $(-\infty ,+\infty )$ ⁠ and then running the linear regression on these transformed values.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] In 1934, Chester Ittner Bliss used the cumulative normal distribution function to perform this mapping and called his model *probit*, an abbreviation of "probability unit".
[src:logistic-regression/logit] This is, however, computationally more expensive.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] In 1944, Joseph Berkson used log of odds and called this function *logit*, an abbreviation of "logistic unit", following the analogy for probit.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] Log odds was used extensively by Charles Sanders Peirce in the late 19th century.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] Barnard in 1949 coined the commonly used term **log-odds**; the log-odds of an event is the logit of the probability of the event.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] Barnard also coined the term *lods* as an abstract form of "log-odds", but suggested that "in practice the term 'odds' should normally be used, since this is more familiar in everyday life".
[src:logistic-regression/logit] Closely related to the logit function (and logit model) are the probit function and probit model.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] The logit and probit are both sigmoid functions with a domain between 0 and 1, which makes them both quantile functions – i.e., inverses of the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of a probability distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] In fact, the logit is the quantile function of the logistic distribution, while the probit is the quantile function of the normal distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] As shown in the graph on the right, the logit and probit functions are extremely similar when the probit function is scaled, so that its slope at *y* = 0 matches the slope of the logit.
[src:logistic-regression/logit] As a result, probit models are sometimes used in place of logit models because for certain applications (e.g., in item response theory) the implementation is easier.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In statistics, **maximum likelihood estimation** (**MLE**) is a method of estimating the parameters of an assumed probability distribution, given some observed data.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This is achieved by maximizing a likelihood function so that, under the assumed statistical model, the observed data is most probable.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The point in the parameter space that maximizes the likelihood function is called the maximum likelihood estimate.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The logic of maximum likelihood is both intuitive and flexible, and as such the method has become a dominant means of statistical inference.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] If the likelihood function is differentiable, the derivative test for finding maxima can be applied.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In some cases, the first-order conditions of the likelihood function can be solved analytically; for instance, the ordinary least squares estimator for a linear regression model maximizes the likelihood when the random errors are assumed to have normal distributions with the same variance.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] From the perspective of Bayesian inference, MLE is generally equivalent to maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimation with a prior distribution that is uniform in the region of interest.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In frequentist inference, MLE is a special case of an extremum estimator, with the objective function being the likelihood.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] We model a set of observations as a random sample from an unknown joint probability distribution which is expressed in terms of a set of parameters.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The goal of maximum likelihood estimation is to determine the parameters for which the observed data have the highest joint probability.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Evaluating the joint density at the observed data sample $\;\mathbf {y} =(y_{1},y_{2},\ldots ,y_{n})\;$ gives a real-valued function, ${\mathcal {L}}_{n}(\theta )={\mathcal {L}}_{n}(\theta ;\mathbf {y} )=f_{n}(\mathbf {y} ;\theta )\;,$ which is called the likelihood function.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Intuitively, this selects the parameter values that make the observed data most probable.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The specific value $~{\hat {\theta }}={\hat {\theta }}_{n}(\mathbf {y} )\in \Theta ~$ that maximizes the likelihood function $\,{\mathcal {L}}_{n}\,$ is called the maximum likelihood estimate.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Further, if the function $\;{\hat {\theta }}_{n}:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \Theta \;$ so defined is measurable, then it is called the maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It is generally a function defined over the sample space, i.e. taking a given sample as its argument.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] A sufficient but not necessary condition for its existence is for the likelihood function to be continuous over a parameter space $\,\Theta \,$ that is compact.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] For an open $\,\Theta \,$ the likelihood function may increase without ever reaching a supremum value.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] For some models, these equations can be explicitly solved for $\,{\widehat {\theta \,}}\,,$ but in general no closed-form solution to the maximization problem is known or available, and an MLE can only be found via numerical optimization.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Another problem is that in finite samples, there may exist multiple roots for the likelihood equations.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] is negative semi-definite at ${\widehat {\theta \,}}$ , as this indicates local concavity.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Conveniently, most common probability distributions – in particular the exponential family – are logarithmically concave.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] While the domain of the likelihood function—the parameter space—is generally a finite-dimensional subset of Euclidean space, additional restrictions sometimes need to be incorporated into the estimation process.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] For instance, in a multivariate normal distribution the covariance matrix $\,\Sigma \,$ must be positive-definite; this restriction can be imposed by replacing $\;\Sigma =\Gamma ^{\mathsf {T}}\Gamma \;,$ where $\Gamma$ is a real upper triangular matrix and $\Gamma ^{\mathsf {T}}$ is its transpose.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] where $~\lambda =\left[\lambda _{1},\lambda _{2},\ldots ,\lambda _{r}\right]^{\mathsf {T}}~$ is a column-vector of Lagrange multipliers and $\;{\frac {\partial h(\theta )^{\mathsf {T}}}{\partial \theta }}\;$ is the k × r Jacobian matrix of partial derivatives.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Naturally, if the constraints are not binding at the maximum, the Lagrange multipliers should be zero.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This in turn allows for a statistical test of the "validity" of the constraint, known as the Lagrange multiplier test.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Nonparametric maximum likelihood estimation can be performed using the empirical likelihood.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] A maximum likelihood estimator is an extremum estimator obtained by maximizing, as a function of *θ*, the objective function ${\widehat {\ell \,}}(\theta \,;x)$ .
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Maximum-likelihood estimators have no optimum properties for finite samples, in the sense that (when evaluated on finite samples) other estimators may have greater concentration around the true parameter-value.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Under the conditions outlined below, the maximum likelihood estimator is consistent.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The consistency means that if the data were generated by $f(\cdot \,;\theta _{0})$ and we have a sufficiently large number of observations *n*, then it is possible to find the value of *θ*0 with arbitrary precision.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In practical applications, data is never generated by $f(\cdot \,;\theta _{0})$ .
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Rather, $f(\cdot \,;\theta _{0})$ is a model, often in idealized form, of the process generated by the data.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It is a common aphorism in statistics that *all models are wrong*.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Thus, true consistency does not occur in practical applications.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Nevertheless, consistency is often considered to be a desirable property for an estimator to have.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] To establish consistency, the following conditions are sufficient.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Compactness: the parameter space Θ of the model is compact.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The identification condition establishes that the log-likelihood has a unique global maximum.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Compactness implies that the likelihood cannot approach the maximum value arbitrarily close at some other point (as demonstrated for example in the picture on the right).
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Compactness is only a sufficient condition and not a necessary condition.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Continuity: the function ln *f*(*x* | *θ*) is continuous in θ for almost all values of x: $\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } {\Bigl [}\;\ln f(x\mid \theta )\;\in \;C^{0}(\Theta )\;{\Bigr ]}=1.$ The continuity here can be replaced with a slightly weaker condition of upper semi-continuity.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The dominance condition can be employed in the case of i.i.d. observations.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In the non-i.i.d. case, the uniform convergence in probability can be checked by showing that the sequence ${\widehat {\ell \,}}(\theta \mid x)$ is stochastically equicontinuous.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Additionally, if (as assumed above) the data were generated by $f(\cdot \,;\theta _{0})$ , then under certain conditions, it can also be shown that the maximum likelihood estimator converges in distribution to a normal distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The maximum likelihood estimator selects the parameter value which gives the observed data the largest possible probability (or probability density, in the continuous case).
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] If the parameter consists of a number of components, then we define their separate maximum likelihood estimators, as the corresponding component of the MLE of the complete parameter.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The MLE is also equivariant with respect to certain transformations of the data.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] and hence the likelihood functions for X and Y differ only by a factor that does not depend on the model parameters.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] For example, the MLE parameters of the log-normal distribution are the same as those of the normal distribution fitted to the logarithm of the data.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In fact, in the log-normal case if $X\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ , then $Y=g(X)=e^{X}$ follows a log-normal distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] As assumed above, if the data were generated by $~f(\cdot \,;\theta _{0})~,$ then under certain conditions, it can also be shown that the maximum likelihood estimator converges in distribution to a normal distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It is √*n* -consistent and asymptotically efficient, meaning that it reaches the Cramér–Rao bound.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In particular, it means that the bias of the maximum likelihood estimator is equal to zero up to the order ⁠1/√n ⁠.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] However, when we consider the higher-order terms in the expansion of the distribution of this estimator, it turns out that *θ*mle has bias of order 1⁄n.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This bias-corrected estimator is *second-order efficient* (at least within the curved exponential family), meaning that it has minimal mean squared error among all second-order bias-corrected estimators, up to the terms of the order ⁠1/ n2 ⁠ .
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It is possible to continue this process, that is to derive the third-order bias-correction term, and so on.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] However, the maximum likelihood estimator is *not* third-order efficient.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] A maximum likelihood estimator coincides with the most probable Bayesian estimator given a uniform prior distribution on the parameters.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] where $\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } (\theta )$ is the prior distribution for the parameter θ and where $\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } (x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n})$ is the probability of the data averaged over all parameters.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Since the denominator is independent of θ, the Bayesian estimator is obtained by maximizing $f(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}\mid \theta )\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } (\theta )$ with respect to θ.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] If we further assume that the prior $\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } (\theta )$ is a uniform distribution, the Bayesian estimator is obtained by maximizing the likelihood function $f(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}\mid \theta )$ .
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Thus the Bayesian estimator coincides with the maximum likelihood estimator for a uniform prior distribution $\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } (\theta )$ .
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In many practical applications in machine learning, maximum-likelihood estimation is used as the model for parameter estimation.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The Bayesian Decision theory is about designing a classifier that minimizes total expected risk, especially, when the costs (the loss function) associated with different decisions are equal, the classifier is minimizing the error over the whole distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Maximum likelihood estimates of parameters can be substituted into expressions for the probability density function, cumulative distribution function, or quantile function, to generate predictions of probabilities or quantiles of out-of-sample events.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This method for predicting probabilities is recommended in statistics text-books and actuarial textbooks, and is widely used in the scientific literature.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] However, maximum likelihood prediction fails to propagate the uncertainty around the maximum likelihood parameter estimates into the prediction.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] As a result, the predicted probabilities are not well calibrated, and should not be expected to correspond to the frequencies of out-of-sample events.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In particular, tail exceedance probabilities and tail exceedance quantiles are typically underestimated, sometimes dramatically.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The underestimation is largest when there is little training data, many parameters being estimated, and for the far tail.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] For cases where this prediction bias is a problem, Bayesian predictions can provide a solution if the prior is chosen so as to reduce or eliminate the bias.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Consider a case where *n* tickets numbered from 1 to *n* are placed in a box and one is selected at random (*see uniform distribution*); thus, the sample size is 1.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] If *n* is unknown, then the maximum likelihood estimator ${\widehat {n}}$ of *n* is the number *m* on the drawn ticket.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] (The likelihood is 0 for *n* < *m*, 1⁄*n* for *n* ≥ *m*, and this is greatest when *n* = *m*.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] As a result, with a sample size of 1, the maximum likelihood estimator for *n* will systematically underestimate *n* by (*n* − 1)/2.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Suppose one wishes to determine just how biased an unfair coin is.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Call the probability of tossing a 'head' *p*.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Suppose the coin is tossed 80 times: i.e. the sample might be something like *x*1 = H, *x*2 = T, ..., *x*80 = T, and the count of the number of heads "H" is observed.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The probability of tossing tails is 1 − *p* (so here *p* is *θ* above).
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Suppose the outcome is 49 heads and 31 tails, and suppose the coin was taken from a box containing three coins: one which gives heads with probability *p* = 1⁄3, one which gives heads with probability *p* = 1⁄2 and another which gives heads with probability *p* = 2⁄3.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The coins have lost their labels, so which one it was is unknown.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Using maximum likelihood estimation, the coin that has the largest likelihood can be found, given the data that were observed.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The likelihood is maximized when p = 2⁄3, and so this is the *maximum likelihood estimate* for p.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Now suppose that there was only one coin but its p could have been any value 0 ≤ p ≤ 1 .
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] and the maximisation is over all possible values 0 ≤ p ≤ 1 .
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The solution that maximizes the likelihood is clearly p = 49⁄80 (since p = 0 and p = 1 result in a likelihood of 0).
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Thus the *maximum likelihood estimator* for p is 49⁄80.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This result is easily generalized by substituting a letter such as s in the place of 49 to represent the observed number of 'successes' of our Bernoulli trials, and a letter such as n in the place of 80 to represent the number of Bernoulli trials.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Exactly the same calculation yields s⁄n which is the maximum likelihood estimator for any sequence of n Bernoulli trials resulting in s 'successes'.
