[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] But because the calculation of the Hessian matrix is computationally costly, numerous alternatives have been proposed.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Other quasi-Newton methods use more elaborate secant updates to give approximation of Hessian matrix.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] BFGS method is not guaranteed to converge unless the function has a quadratic Taylor expansion near an optimum.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Another popular method is to replace the Hessian with the Fisher information matrix, ${\mathcal {I}}(\theta )=\operatorname {\mathbb {E} } \left[\mathbf {H} _{r}\left({\widehat {\theta }}\right)\right]$ , giving us the Fisher scoring algorithm.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This procedure is standard in the estimation of many methods, such as generalized linear models.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Although popular, quasi-Newton methods may converge to a stationary point that is not necessarily a local or global maximum, but rather a local minimum or a saddle point.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Therefore, it is important to assess the validity of the obtained solution to the likelihood equations, by verifying that the Hessian, evaluated at the solution, is both negative definite and well-conditioned.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Early users of maximum likelihood include Carl Friedrich Gauss, Pierre-Simon Laplace, Thorvald N.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It was Ronald Fisher however, between 1912 and 1922, who single-handedly created the modern version of the method.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Maximum-likelihood estimation finally transcended heuristic justification in a proof published by Samuel S.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Wilks in 1938, now called Wilks' theorem.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The theorem shows that the error in the logarithm of likelihood values for estimates from multiple independent observations is asymptotically *χ* 2-distributed, which enables convenient determination of a confidence region around any estimate of the parameters.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The only difficult part of Wilks' proof depends on the expected value of the Fisher information matrix, which is provided by a theorem proven by Fisher.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Wilks continued to improve on the generality of the theorem throughout his life, with his most general proof published in 1962.
[src:logistic-regression/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Reviews of the development of maximum likelihood estimation have been provided by a number of authors.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] In statistics, **multinomial logistic regression** is a classification method that generalizes logistic regression to multiclass problems, i.e. with more than two possible discrete outcomes.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] That is, it is a model that is used to predict the probabilities of the different possible outcomes of a categorically distributed dependent variable, given a set of independent variables (which may be real-valued, binary-valued, categorical-valued, etc.).
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Multinomial logistic regression is known by a variety of other names, including **polytomous LR**, **multiclass LR**, **softmax regression**, **multinomial logit** (**mlogit**), the **maximum entropy** (**MaxEnt**) classifier, and the **conditional maximum entropy model**.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Multinomial logistic regression is used when the dependent variable in question is nominal (equivalently *categorical*, meaning that it falls into any one of a set of categories that cannot be ordered in any meaningful way) and for which there are more than two categories.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] These are all statistical classification problems.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] They all have in common a dependent variable to be predicted that comes from one of a limited set of items that cannot be meaningfully ordered, as well as a set of independent variables (also known as features, explanators, etc.), which are used to predict the dependent variable.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Multinomial logistic regression is a particular solution to classification problems that use a linear combination of the observed features and some problem-specific parameters to estimate the probability of each particular value of the dependent variable.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The best values of the parameters for a given problem are usually determined from some training data (e.g. some people for whom both the diagnostic test results and blood types are known, or some examples of known words being spoken).
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The multinomial logistic model assumes that data are case-specific; that is, each independent variable has a single value for each case.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] If the multinomial logit is used to model choices, it relies on the assumption of independence of irrelevant alternatives (IIA), which is not always desirable.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This assumption states that the odds of preferring one class over another do not depend on the presence or absence of other "irrelevant" alternatives.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] For example, the relative probabilities of taking a car or bus to work do not change if a bicycle is added as an additional possibility.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This allows the choice of *K* alternatives to be modeled as a set of *K* − 1 independent binary choices, in which one alternative is chosen as a "pivot" and the other *K* − 1 compared against it, one at a time.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The IIA hypothesis is a core hypothesis in rational choice theory; however numerous studies in psychology show that individuals often violate this assumption when making choices.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] An example of a problem case arises if choices include a car and a blue bus.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Suppose the odds ratio between the two is 1 : 1.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Now if the option of a red bus is introduced, a person may be indifferent between a red and a blue bus, and hence may exhibit a car : blue bus : red bus odds ratio of 1 : 0.5 : 0.5, thus maintaining a 1 : 1 ratio of car : any bus while adopting a changed car : blue bus ratio of 1 : 0.5.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Here the red bus option was not in fact irrelevant, because a red bus was a perfect substitute for a blue bus.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] If the multinomial logit is used to model choices, it may in some situations impose too much constraint on the relative preferences between the different alternatives.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] It is especially important to take into account if the analysis aims to predict how choices would change if one alternative were to disappear (for instance if one political candidate withdraws from a three candidate race).
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Other models like the nested logit or the multinomial probit may be used in such cases as they allow for violation of the IIA.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] There are multiple equivalent ways to describe the mathematical model underlying multinomial logistic regression.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This can make it difficult to compare different treatments of the subject in different texts.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The article on logistic regression presents a number of equivalent formulations of simple logistic regression, and many of these have analogues in the multinomial logit model.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] where **X***i* is the vector of explanatory variables describing observation *i*, **β***k* is a vector of weights (or regression coefficients) corresponding to outcome *k*, and score(**X***i*, *k*) is the score associated with assigning observation *i* to category *k*.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] In discrete choice theory, where observations represent people and outcomes represent choices, the score is considered the utility associated with person *i* choosing outcome *k*.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The predicted outcome is the one with the highest score.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] In particular, in the multinomial logit model, the score can directly be converted to a probability value, indicating the probability of observation *i* choosing outcome *k* given the measured characteristics of the observation.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This provides a principled way of incorporating the prediction of a particular multinomial logit model into a larger procedure that may involve multiple such predictions, each with a possibility of error.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Without such means of combining predictions, errors tend to multiply.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] For example, imagine a large predictive model that is broken down into a series of submodels where the prediction of a given submodel is used as the input of another submodel, and that prediction is in turn used as the input into a third submodel, etc.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] If each submodel has 90% accuracy in its predictions, and there are five submodels in series, then the overall model has only 0.95 = 59% accuracy.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] If each submodel has 80% accuracy, then overall accuracy drops to 0.85 = 33% accuracy.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This issue is known as error propagation and is a serious problem in real-world predictive models, which are usually composed of numerous parts.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Predicting probabilities of each possible outcome, rather than simply making a single optimal prediction, is one means of alleviating this issue.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The basic setup is the same as in logistic regression, the only difference being that the dependent variables are categorical rather than binary, i.e. there are *K* possible outcomes rather than just two.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The following description is somewhat shortened; for more details, consult the logistic regression article.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Specifically, it is assumed that we have a series of *N* observed data points.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Each data point *i* (ranging from 1 to *N*) consists of a set of *M* explanatory variables *x*1,*i* ...
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] *x**M,i* (also known as independent variables, predictor variables, features, etc.), and an associated categorical outcome *Y**i* (also known as dependent variable, response variable), which can take on one of *K* possible values.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] These possible values represent logically separate categories (e.g. different political parties, blood types, etc.), and are often described mathematically by arbitrarily assigning each a number from 1 to *K*.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The explanatory variables and outcome represent observed properties of the data points, and are often thought of as originating in the observations of *N* "experiments" — although an "experiment" may consist of nothing more than gathering data.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] In the process, the model attempts to explain the relative effect of differing explanatory variables on the outcome.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] where $\beta _{m,k}$ is a regression coefficient associated with the *m*th explanatory variable and the *k*th outcome.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] where ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{k}$ is the set of regression coefficients associated with outcome *k*, and $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ (a row vector) is the set of explanatory variables associated with observation *i*, prepended by a 1 in entry 0.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] To arrive at the multinomial logit model, one can imagine, for *K* possible outcomes, running *K* independent binary logistic regression models, in which one outcome is chosen as a "pivot" and then the other *K* − 1 outcomes are separately regressed against the pivot outcome.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This formulation is also known as the Additive Log Ratio transform commonly used in compositional data analysis.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] In other applications it’s referred to as “relative risk”.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The fact that we run multiple regressions reveals why the model relies on the assumption of independence of irrelevant alternatives described above.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The solution is typically found using an iterative procedure such as generalized iterative scaling, iteratively reweighted least squares (IRLS), by means of gradient-based optimization algorithms such as L-BFGS, or by specialized coordinate descent algorithms.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The formulation of binary logistic regression as a log-linear model can be directly extended to multi-way regression.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The reason why we need to add a term to ensure normalization, rather than multiply as is usual, is because we have taken the logarithm of the probabilities.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The quantity *Z* is called the partition function for the distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Note that this factor is "constant" in the sense that it is not a function of *Y**i*, which is the variable over which the probability distribution is defined.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] However, it is definitely not constant with respect to the explanatory variables, or crucially, with respect to the unknown regression coefficients ***β****k*, which we will need to determine through some sort of optimization procedure.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The reason is that the effect of exponentiating the values $s_{1},\ldots ,s_{K}$ is to exaggerate the differences between them.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] As a result, $\operatorname {softmax} (k,s_{1},\ldots ,s_{K})$ will return a value close to 0 whenever $s_{k}$ is significantly less than the maximum of all the values, and will return a value close to 1 when applied to the maximum value, unless it is extremely close to the next-largest value.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The softmax function thus serves as the equivalent of the logistic function in binary logistic regression.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Note that not all of the ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{k}$ vectors of coefficients are uniquely identifiable.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This is due to the fact that all probabilities must sum to 1, making one of them completely determined once all the rest are known.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] As a result, there are only $K-1$ separately specifiable probabilities, and hence $K-1$ separately identifiable vectors of coefficients.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] As a result, it is conventional to set $\mathbf {C} =-{\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{K}$ (or alternatively, one of the other coefficient vectors).
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Essentially, we set the constant so that one of the vectors becomes ${\boldsymbol {0}}$ , and all of the other vectors get transformed into the difference between those vectors and the vector we chose.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This is equivalent to "pivoting" around one of the *K* choices, and examining how much better or worse all of the other *K* − 1 choices are, relative to the choice we are pivoting around.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Other than the prime symbols on the regression coefficients, this is exactly the same as the form of the model described above, in terms of *K* − 1 independent two-way regressions.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] It is also possible to formulate multinomial logistic regression as a latent variable model, following the two-way latent variable model described for binary logistic regression.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This formulation is common in the theory of discrete choice models, and makes it easier to compare multinomial logistic regression to the related multinomial probit model, as well as to extend it to more complex models.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] where $\varepsilon _{k}\sim \operatorname {EV} _{1}(0,1),$ i.e. a standard type-1 extreme value distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This latent variable can be thought of as the utility associated with data point *i* choosing outcome *k*, where there is some randomness in the actual amount of utility obtained, which accounts for other unmodeled factors that go into the choice.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Since the latent variables are continuous, the probability of two having exactly the same value is 0, so we ignore the scenario.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Together with the previous point, this shows that the use of a standard extreme-value distribution (location 0, scale 1) for the error variables entails no loss of generality over using an arbitrary extreme-value distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] In fact, the model is nonidentifiable (no single set of optimal coefficients) if the more general distribution is used.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Because only differences of vectors of regression coefficients are used, adding an arbitrary constant to all coefficient vectors has no effect on the model.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] This means that, just as in the log-linear model, only *K* − 1 of the coefficient vectors are identifiable, and the last one can be set to an arbitrary value (e.g.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Actually finding the values of the above probabilities is somewhat difficult, and is a problem of computing a particular order statistic (the first, i.e. maximum) of a set of values.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] However, it can be shown that the resulting expressions are the same as in above formulations, i.e. the two are equivalent.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] When using multinomial logistic regression, one category of the dependent variable is chosen as the reference category.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] Separate odds ratios are determined for all independent variables for each category of the dependent variable with the exception of the reference category, which is omitted from the analysis.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The exponential beta coefficient represents the change in the odds of the dependent variable being in a particular category vis-a-vis the reference category, associated with a one unit change of the corresponding independent variable.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] The observed values $y_{i}\in \{1,\dots ,K\}$ for $i=1,\dots ,n$ of the explained variables are considered as realizations of stochastically independent, categorically distributed random variables $Y_{1},\dots ,Y_{n}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] where the index i denotes the observations 1 to *n* and the index j denotes the classes 1 to *K*. $\delta _{j,y_{i}}={\begin{cases}1,{\text{ for }}j=y_{i}\\0,{\text{ otherwise}}\end{cases}}$ is the Kronecker delta.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] In natural language processing, multinomial LR classifiers are commonly used as an alternative to naive Bayes classifiers because they do not assume statistical independence of the random variables (commonly known as *features*) that serve as predictors.
[src:logistic-regression/multinomial-logistic-regression] However, learning in such a model is slower than for a naive Bayes classifier, and thus may not be appropriate given a very large number of classes to learn.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] An **odds ratio** (**OR**) is a statistic that quantifies the strength of the association between two events, A and B.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The odds ratio is defined as the ratio of the odds of event A taking place in the presence of B, and the odds of A in the absence of B.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Due to symmetry, odds ratio reciprocally calculates the ratio of the odds of B occurring in the presence of A, and the odds of B in the absence of A.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Two events are independent if and only if the OR equals 1, i.e., the odds of one event are the same in either the presence or absence of the other event.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] If the OR is greater than 1, then A and B are associated (correlated) in the sense that, compared to the absence of B, the presence of B raises the odds of A, and symmetrically the presence of A raises the odds of B.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Conversely, if the OR is less than 1, then A and B are negatively correlated, and the presence of one event reduces the odds of the other event occurring.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Note that the odds ratio is symmetric in the two events, and no causal direction is implied (correlation does not imply causation): an OR greater than 1 does not establish that B causes A, or that A causes B.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Two similar statistics that are often used to quantify associations are the relative risk (RR) and the absolute risk reduction (ARR).
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Often, the parameter of greatest interest is actually the RR, which is the ratio of the probabilities analogous to the odds used in the OR.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] However, available data frequently do not allow for the computation of the RR or the ARR, but do allow for the computation of the OR, as in case-control studies, as explained below.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] On the other hand, if one of the properties (A or B) is sufficiently rare (in epidemiology this is called the rare disease assumption), then the OR is approximately equal to the corresponding RR.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The OR plays an important role in the logistic model.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] If we flip an unbiased coin, the probability of getting heads and the probability of getting tails are equal — both are 50%.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Imagine we get a biased coin such that, if one flips it, one is twice as likely to get heads than tails (i.e., the *odds* double: from 1:1 to 2:1).
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The new probabilities would be 66.666...% for heads and 33.333...% for tails.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Suppose a radiation leak in a village of 1,000 people increased the incidence of a rare disease.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The total number of people exposed to the radiation was $V_{E}=400,$ out of which $D_{E}=20$ developed the disease and $H_{E}=380$ stayed healthy.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The total number of people not exposed was $V_{N}=600,$ out of which $D_{N}=6$ developed the disease and $H_{N}=594$ stayed healthy.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The *risk* of developing the disease given exposure is $D_{E}/V_{E}=20/400=.05$ and of developing the disease given non-exposure is $D_{N}/V_{N}=6/600=.01$ .
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] One obvious way to compare the risks is to use the ratio of the two, the *relative risk*.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] As illustrated by this example, in a rare-disease case like this, the relative risk and the odds ratio are almost the same.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] By definition, rare disease implies that $V_{E}\approx H_{E}$ and $V_{N}\approx H_{N}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Thus, the denominators in the relative risk and odds ratio are almost the same ( $400\approx 380$ and $600\approx 594)$ .
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Relative risk is easier to understand than the odds ratio, but one reason to use odds ratio is that usually, data on the entire population is not available and random sampling must be used.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] In the example above, if it were very costly to interview villagers and find out if they were exposed to the radiation, then the prevalence of radiation exposure would not be known, and neither would the values of $V_{E}$ or $V_{N}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] One could take a random sample of fifty villagers, but quite possibly such a random sample would not include anybody with the disease, since only 2.6% of the population are diseased.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Instead, one might use a case-control study in which all 26 diseased villagers are interviewed as well as a random sample of 26 who do not have the disease.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The odds in this sample of getting the disease given that someone is exposed is 20/10 and the odds given that someone is not exposed is 6/16.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The odds ratio is thus ${\frac {20/10}{6/16}}\approx 5.3$ , quite close to the odds ratio calculated for the entire village.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The relative risk, however, cannot be calculated, because it is the ratio of the risks of getting the disease and we would need $V_{E}$ and $V_{N}$ to figure those out.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Because the study selected for people with the disease, half the people in the sample have the disease and it is known that that is more than the population-wide prevalence.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Therefore, the numbers of diseased and healthy within exposed, and diseased and healthy within non-exposed, are not addable.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] It is standard in the medical literature to calculate the odds ratio and then use the rare-disease assumption (which is usually reasonable) to claim that the relative risk is approximately equal to it.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This not only allows for the use of case-control studies, but makes controlling for confounding variables such as weight or age using regression analysis easier and has the desirable properties discussed in other sections of this article of invariance and insensitivity to the type of sampling.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The odds ratio is the ratio of the odds of an event occurring in one group to the odds of it occurring in another group.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The term is also used to refer to sample-based estimates of this ratio.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] These groups might be men and women, an experimental group and a control group, or any other dichotomous classification.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] An odds ratio of 1 indicates that the condition or event under study is equally likely to occur in both groups.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] An odds ratio greater than 1 indicates that the condition or event is more likely to occur in the first group.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] And an odds ratio less than 1 indicates that the condition or event is less likely to occur in the first group.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The odds ratio must be nonnegative if it is defined.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] It is undefined if *p*2*q*1 equals zero, i.e., if *p*2 equals zero or *q*1 equals zero.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The odds ratio can also be defined in terms of the joint probability distribution of two binary random variables.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] where p11, p10, p01 and p00 are non-negative "cell probabilities" that sum to one.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Note that the odds ratio is also the product of the probabilities of the "concordant cells" (X = Y) divided by the product of the probabilities of the "discordant cells" (X ≠ Y).
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] However, in some applications the labelling of categories as zero and one is arbitrary, so there is nothing special about concordant versus discordant values in these applications.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Other measures of effect size for binary data such as the relative risk do not have this symmetry property.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] In this case, the odds ratio equals one, and conversely the odds ratio can only equal one if the joint probabilities can be factored in this way.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Thus the odds ratio equals one if and only if *X* and *Y* are independent.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The odds ratio is a function of the cell probabilities, and conversely, the cell probabilities can be recovered given knowledge of the odds ratio and the marginal probabilities *P*(*X* = 1) = *p*11 + *p*10 and *P*(*Y* = 1) = *p*11 + *p*01.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Once we have *p*11, the other three cell probabilities can easily be recovered from the marginal probabilities.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Suppose that in a sample of 100 men, 90 drank wine in the previous week (so 10 did not), while in a sample of 80 women only 20 drank wine in the same period (so 60 did not).
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Alternatively, the odds of a man drinking wine are 90 to 10, or 9:1, while the odds of a woman drinking wine are only 20 to 60, or 1:3 = 0.33.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The odds ratio is thus 9/0.33, or 27, showing that men are much more likely to drink wine than women.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This example also shows how odds ratios are sometimes sensitive in stating relative positions: in this sample men are (90/100)/(20/80) = 3.6 times as likely to have drunk wine than women, but have 27 times the odds.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The logarithm of the odds ratio, the difference of the logits of the probabilities, tempers this effect, and also makes the measure symmetric with respect to the ordering of groups.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] For example, using natural logarithms, an odds ratio of 27/1 maps to 3.296, and an odds ratio of 1/27 maps to −3.296.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Several approaches to statistical inference for odds ratios have been developed.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] One approach to inference uses large sample approximations to the sampling distribution of the log odds ratio (the natural logarithm of the odds ratio).
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This is an asymptotic approximation, and will not give a meaningful result if any of the cell counts are very small.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] If *L* is the sample log odds ratio, an approximate 95% confidence interval for the population log odds ratio is *L* ± 1.96SE.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This can be mapped to exp(*L* − 1.96SE), exp(*L* + 1.96SE) to obtain a 95% confidence interval for the odds ratio.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] If we wish to test the hypothesis that the population odds ratio equals one, the two-sided p-value is 2*P*(*Z* < −|*L*|/SE), where *P* denotes a probability, and *Z* denotes a standard normal random variable.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] An alternative approach to inference for odds ratios looks at the distribution of the data conditionally on the marginal frequencies of *X* and *Y*.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] An advantage of this approach is that the sampling distribution of the odds ratio can be expressed exactly.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Logistic regression is one way to generalize the odds ratio beyond two binary variables.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Suppose we have a binary response variable *Y* and a binary predictor variable *X*, and in addition we have other predictor variables *Z*1, ..., *Zp* that may or may not be binary.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] If we use multiple logistic regression to regress *Y* on *X*, *Z1*, ..., *Zp*, then the estimated coefficient ${\hat {\beta }}_{x}$ for *X* is related to a conditional odds ratio.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] so $\exp({\hat {\beta }}_{x})$ is an estimate of this conditional odds ratio.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The interpretation of $\exp({\hat {\beta }}_{x})$ is as an estimate of the odds ratio between *Y* and *X* when the values of *Z*1, ..., *Zp* are held fixed.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] If the data form a "population sample", then the cell probabilities ${\widehat {p\,}}_{ij}$ are interpreted as the frequencies of each of the four groups in the population as defined by their *X* and *Y* values.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] In many settings it is impractical to obtain a population sample, so a selected sample is used.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] For example, we may choose to sample units with *X* = 1 with a given probability *f*, regardless of their frequency in the population (which would necessitate sampling units with *X* = 0 with probability 1 − *f*).
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The *odds ratio* *p*11*p*00 / *p*01*p*10 for this distribution does not depend on the value of *f*.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This shows that the odds ratio (and consequently the log odds ratio) is invariant to non-random sampling based on one of the variables being studied.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Note however that the standard error of the log odds ratio does depend on the value of *f*.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] In both these settings, the odds ratio can be calculated from the selected sample, without biasing the results relative to what would have been obtained for a population sample.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Due to the widespread use of logistic regression, the odds ratio is widely used in many fields of medical and social science research.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The odds ratio is commonly used in survey research, in epidemiology, and to express the results of some clinical trials, such as in case-control studies.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] It is often abbreviated "OR" in reports.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] When data from multiple surveys is combined, it will often be expressed as "pooled OR".
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] As explained in the "Motivating Example" section, the relative risk is usually better than the odds ratio for understanding the relation between risk and some variable such as radiation or a new drug.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] That section also explains that if the rare disease assumption holds, the odds ratio is a good approximation to relative risk and that it has some advantages over relative risk.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] When the rare disease assumption does not hold, the unadjusted odds ratio will be greater than the relative risk, but novel methods can easily use the same data to estimate the relative risk, risk differences, base probabilities, or other quantities.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] where *R**C* is the absolute risk of the unexposed group.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] If the rare disease assumption does not apply, the odds ratio may be very different from the relative risk and should not be interpreted as a relative risk.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Consider the death rate of men and women passengers when a ship sank.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Of 462 women, 154 died and 308 survived.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Clearly a man on the ship was more likely to die than a woman, but how much more likely?
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Since over half the passengers died, the rare disease assumption is strongly violated.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] To compute the odds ratio, note that for women the odds of dying were 1 to 2 (154/308).
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Men had ten times the odds of dying as women.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] For women, the probability of death was 33% (154/462).
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] A man had 2.5 times a woman's probability of dying.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Odds ratios have often been confused with relative risk in medical literature.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] For non-statisticians, the odds ratio is a difficult concept to comprehend, and it gives a more impressive figure for the effect.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] However, most authors consider that the relative risk is readily understood.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] In one study, members of a national disease foundation were actually 3.5 times more likely than nonmembers to have heard of a common treatment for that disease – but the odds ratio was 24 and the paper stated that members were ‘more than 20-fold more likely to have heard of’ the treatment.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] A study of papers published in two journals reported that 26% of the articles that used an odds ratio interpreted it as a risk ratio.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This may reflect the simple process of uncomprehending authors choosing the most impressive-looking and publishable figure.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] But its use may in some cases be deliberately deceptive.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] It has been suggested that the odds ratio should only be presented as a measure of effect size when the risk ratio cannot be estimated directly, but with newly available methods it is always possible to estimate the risk ratio, which should generally be used instead.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] While relative risks are potentially easier to interpret for a general audience, there are mathematical and conceptual advantages when using an odds-ratio instead of a relative risk, particularly in regression models.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] For that reason, there is not a consensus within the fields of epidemiology or biostatistics that relative risks or odds-ratios should be preferred when both can be validly used, such as in clinical trials and cohort studies.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The odds ratio has another unique property of being directly mathematically invertible whether analyzing the OR as either disease survival or disease onset incidence – where the OR for survival is direct reciprocal of 1/OR for risk.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This is known as the 'invariance of the odds ratio'.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] In contrast, the relative risk does not possess this mathematical invertible property when studying disease survival vs. onset incidence.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Suppose in a clinical trial, one has an adverse event risk of 4/100 in drug group, and 2/100 in placebo... yielding a RR=2 and OR=2.04166 for drug-vs-placebo adverse risk.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] However, if analysis was inverted and adverse events were instead analyzed as event-free survival, then the drug group would have a rate of 96/100, and placebo group would have a rate of 98/100—yielding a drug-vs-placebo a RR=0.9796 for survival, but an OR=0.48979.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] As one can see, a RR of 0.9796 is clearly not the reciprocal of a RR of 2.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] In contrast, an OR of 0.48979 is indeed the direct reciprocal of an OR of 2.04166.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This is again what is called the 'invariance of the odds ratio', and why a RR for survival is not the same as a RR for risk, while the OR has this symmetrical property when analyzing either survival or adverse risk.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The danger to clinical interpretation for the OR comes when the adverse event rate is not rare, thereby exaggerating differences when the OR rare-disease assumption is not met.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] On the other hand, when the disease is rare, using a RR for survival (e.g. the RR=0.9796 from above example) can clinically hide and conceal an important doubling of adverse risk associated with a drug or exposure.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The **sample odds ratio** *n*11*n*00 / *n*10*n*01 is easy to calculate, and for moderate and large samples performs well as an estimator of the population odds ratio.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] When one or more of the cells in the contingency table can have a small value, the sample odds ratio can be biased and exhibit high variance.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] A number of alternative estimators of the odds ratio have been proposed to address limitations of the sample odds ratio.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] One alternative estimator is the conditional maximum likelihood estimator, which conditions on the row and column margins when forming the likelihood to maximize (as in Fisher's exact test).
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Another alternative estimator is the Mantel–Haenszel estimator.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] There are various other summary statistics for contingency tables that measure association between two events, such as Yule's *Y*, Yule's *Q*; these two are normalized so they are 0 for independent events, 1 for perfectly correlated, −1 for perfectly negatively correlated.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Edwards studied these and argued that these measures of association must be functions of the odds ratio, which he referred to as the cross-ratio.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] A case-control study involves selecting representative samples of cases and controls who do, and do not, have some disease, respectively.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] These samples are usually independent of each other.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The prior prevalence of exposure to some risk factor is observed in subjects from both samples.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This permits the estimation of the odds ratio for disease in exposed vs. unexposed people as noted above.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Sometimes, however, it makes sense to match cases to controls on one or more confounding variables.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] In this case, the prior exposure of interest is determined for each case and her/his matched control.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The data can be summarized in the following table.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This table gives the exposure status of the matched pairs of subjects.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The exposure of matched case and control pairs is correlated due to the similar values of their shared confounding variables.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] The following derivation is due to Breslow & Day.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] We consider each pair as belonging to a stratum with identical values of the confounding variables.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Conditioned on belonging to the same stratum, the exposure status of cases and controls are independent of each other.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] be the probability that a control patient is not exposed.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Then the probability that a case is exposed and a control is not is $p_{1}q_{0}$ , and the probability that a control is exposed and a case in not is $p_{0}q_{1}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] We assume that ψ is constant across strata.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Now concordant pairs in which either both the case and the control are exposed, or neither are exposed tell us nothing about the odds of exposure in cases relative to the odds of exposure among controls.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Now ${\hat {\pi }}$ is the maximum likelihood estimate of π, and ψ is a monotonic function of ${\hat {\pi }}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] It follows that ${\hat {\psi }}$ is the conditional maximum likelihood estimate of ${\hat {\psi }}$ given the number of discordant pairs.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Rothman et al. give an alternate derivation of ${\hat {\psi }}$ by showing that it is a special case of the Mantel-Haenszel estimate of the intra-strata odds ratio for stratified 2x2 tables.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] They also reference Breslow & Day as providing the derivation given here.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Hence, we can test the null hypothesis that $\psi =1$ by testing the null hypothesis that $\pi =0.5$ .
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] There are a number of ways to calculate a confidence interval for π.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Let ${\hat {\pi }}_{LB}$ and ${\hat {\pi }}_{UB}$ denote the lower and upper bound of a confidence interval for π, respectively.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Matched 2x2 tables may also be analyzed using conditional logistic regression.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This technique has the advantage of allowing users to regress case-control status against multiple risk factors from matched case-control data.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] McEvoy et al. studied the use of cell phones by drivers as a risk factor for automobile crashes in a case-crossover study.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] All study subjects were involved in an automobile crash requiring hospital attendance.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Each driver's cell phone use at the time of her/his crash was compared to her/his cell phone use in a control interval at the same time of day one week earlier.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] We would expect that a person's cell phone use at the time of the crash would be correlated with his/her use one week earlier.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Comparing usage during the crash and control intervals adjusts for driver's characteristics and the time of day and day of the week.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] There were 5 drivers who used their phones in both intervals, 27 who used them in the crash but not the control interval, 6 who used them in the control but not the crash interval, and 288 who did not use them in either interval.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Testing the null hypothesis that ${\hat {\psi }}=1$ is the same as testing the null hypothesis that ${\hat {\pi }}=0.5$ given 27 out of 33 discordant pairs in which the driver was using her/his phone at the time of his crash.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This statistic has one degree of freedom and yields a *P* value of 0.0003.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] This allows us to reject the hypothesis that cell phone use has no effect on the risk of automobile crashes ( $\psi =1$ ) with a high level of statistical significance.
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] Using Wilson's method, a 95% confidence interval for π is (0.6561, 0.9139).
[src:logistic-regression/odds-ratio] (McEvoy et al. analyzed their data using conditional logistic regression and obtained almost identical results to those given here.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] In statistics, the **ordered logit model** or **proportional odds logistic regression** is an ordinal regression model—that is, a regression model for ordinal dependent variables—first considered by Peter McCullagh.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] It can be thought of as an extension of the logistic regression model that applies to dichotomous dependent variables, allowing for more than two (ordered) response categories.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] The model only applies to data that meet the *proportional odds assumption*, the meaning of which can be exemplified as follows.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] Suppose there are five outcomes: "poor", "fair", "good", "very good", and "excellent".
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] We assume that the probabilities of these outcomes are given by *p*1(*x*), *p*2(*x*), *p*3(*x*), *p*4(*x*), *p*5(*x*), all of which are functions of some independent variable(s) *x*.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] The **proportional odds assumption** states that the numbers added to each of these logarithms to get the next are the same regardless of *x*.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] Ordered logit can be derived from a latent-variable model, similar to the one from which binary logistic regression can be derived.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] where the parameters $\mu _{i}$ are the externally imposed endpoints of the observable categories.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] Then the ordered logit technique will use the observations on *y*, which are a form of censored data on *y**, to fit the parameter vector $\beta$ .
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] As with most statistical models, maximum likelihood estimation or Bayesian inference are the most common ways of identifying the parameters.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] The estimated values indicate the direction and magnitude of the effect of each independent variable on the likelihood of the dependent variable falling into a higher category.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] Ordered logistic regressions have been used in multiple fields, such as transportation, marketing or disaster management.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] In clinical research, the effect a drug may have on a patient may be modeled with ordinal regression.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] Independent variables may include the use or non-use of the drug, as well as control variables such as demographics and details from medical history.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] The dependent variable could be ranked on the following list: complete cure, improved symptoms, no change, worsened symptoms, or death.
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] Another example application are Likert-type items commonly employed in survey research, where respondents rate their agreement on an ordered scale (e.g., "Strongly disagree" to "Strongly agree").
[src:logistic-regression/ordered-logit] The ordered logit model provides an appropriate fit to these data, preserving the ordering of response options while making no assumptions of the interval distances between options.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] In statistics, a **probit model** is a type of regression where the dependent variable can take only two values, for example married or not married.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] The word is a portmanteau, coming from ***prob**ability* + *un**it***.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] The purpose of the model is to estimate the probability that an observation with particular characteristics will fall into a specific one of the categories; moreover, classifying observations based on their predicted probabilities is a type of binary classification model.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] A probit model is a popular specification for a binary response model.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] As such it treats the same set of problems as does logistic regression using similar techniques.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] When viewed in the generalized linear model framework, the probit model employs a probit link function.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] It is most often estimated using the maximum likelihood procedure, such an estimation being called a **probit regression**.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Suppose a response variable *Y* is *binary*, that is it can have only two possible outcomes which we will denote as 1 and 0.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] For example, *Y* may represent presence/absence of a certain condition, success/failure of some device, answer yes/no on a survey, etc.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] We also have a vector of regressors *X*, which are assumed to influence the outcome *Y*.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] where *P* is the probability and $\Phi$ is the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of the standard normal distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] The parameters *β* are typically estimated by maximum likelihood.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] It is possible to motivate the probit model as a latent variable model.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Suppose data set $\{y_{i},x_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n}$ contains *n* independent statistical units corresponding to the model above.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] where $x_{i}$ is a vector of $K\times 1$ inputs, and $\beta$ is a $K\times 1$ vector of coefficients.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] The estimator ${\hat {\beta }}$ which maximizes this function will be consistent, asymptotically normal and efficient provided that $\operatorname {E} [XX^{\operatorname {T} }]$ exists and is not singular.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] It can be shown that this log-likelihood function is globally concave in $\beta$ , and therefore standard numerical algorithms for optimization will converge rapidly to the unique maximum.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] and $\varphi =\Phi '$ is the Probability Density Function (PDF) of standard normal distribution.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Semi-parametric and non-parametric maximum likelihood methods for probit-type and other related models are also available.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] This method can be applied only when there are many observations of response variable $y_{i}$ having the same value of the vector of regressors $x_{i}$ (such situation may be referred to as "many observations per cell").
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] More specifically, the model can be formulated as follows.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Suppose among *n* observations $\{y_{i},x_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n}$ there are only *T* distinct values of the regressors, which can be denoted as $\{x_{(1)},\ldots ,x_{(T)}\}$ .
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Let $n_{t}$ be the number of observations with $x_{i}=x_{(t)},$ and $r_{t}$ the number of such observations with $y_{i}=1$ .
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] We assume that there are indeed "many" observations per each "cell": for each $t,\lim _{n\rightarrow \infty }n_{t}/n=c_{t}>0$ .
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] It can be shown that this estimator is consistent (as *n*→∞ and *T* fixed), asymptotically normal and efficient.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Its advantage is the presence of a closed-form formula for the estimator.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] However, it is only meaningful to carry out this analysis when individual observations are not available, only their aggregated counts $r_{t}$ , $n_{t}$ , and $x_{(t)}$ (for example in the analysis of voting behavior).
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Gibbs sampling of a probit model is possible with the introduction of normally distributed latent variables *z*, which are observed as 1 if positive and 0 otherwise.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] This approach was introduced in Albert and Chib (1993), which demonstrated how Gibbs sampling could be applied to binary and polychotomous response models within a Bayesian framework.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] The result for ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ is given in the article on Bayesian linear regression, although specified with different notation, while the conditional posterior distributions of the latent variables follow a truncated normal distribution within the given ranges.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] The notation $[z_{i}<0]$ is the Iverson bracket, sometimes written ${\mathcal {I}}(z_{i}<0)$ or similar.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Thus, knowledge of the observed outcomes serves to restrict the support of the latent variables.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Sampling of the weights ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ given the latent vector $\mathbf {z}$ from the multinormal distribution is standard.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] For sampling the latent variables from the truncated normal posterior distributions, one can take advantage of the inverse-cdf method, implemented in the following R vectorized function, making it straightforward to implement the method.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] See Logistic regression § Model for details.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Consider the latent variable model formulation of the probit model.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] When the variance of $\varepsilon$ conditional on x is not constant but dependent on x , then the heteroscedasticity issue arises.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] Under heteroskedasticity, the probit estimator for $\beta$ is usually inconsistent, and most of the tests about the coefficients are invalid.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] More importantly, the estimator for $P(y=1\mid x)$ becomes inconsistent, too.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] To deal with this problem, the original model needs to be transformed to be homoskedastic.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] When the assumption that $\varepsilon$ is normally distributed fails to hold, then a functional form misspecification issue arises: if the model is still estimated as a probit model, the estimators of the coefficients $\beta$ are inconsistent.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] For instance, if $\varepsilon$ follows a logistic distribution in the true model, but the model is estimated by probit, the estimates will be generally smaller than the true value.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] However, the inconsistency of the coefficient estimates is practically irrelevant because the estimates for the partial effects, $\partial P(y=1\mid x)/\partial x_{i'}$ , will be close to the estimates given by the true logit model.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] To avoid the issue of distribution misspecification, one may adopt a general distribution assumption for the error term, such that many different types of distribution can be included in the model.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] The cost is heavier computation and lower accuracy for the increase of the number of parameter.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] In most of the cases in practice where the distribution form is misspecified, the estimators for the coefficients are inconsistent, but estimators for the conditional probability and the partial effects are still very good.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] One can also take semi-parametric or non-parametric approaches, e.g., via local-likelihood or nonparametric quasi-likelihood methods, which avoid assumptions on a parametric form for the index function and is robust to the choice of the link function (e.g., probit or logit).
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] The probit model is usually credited to Chester Bliss, who coined the term "probit" in 1934, and to John Gaddum (1933), who systematized earlier work.
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] However, the basic model dates to the Weber–Fechner law by Gustav Fechner, published in Fechner (1860), and was repeatedly rediscovered until the 1930s; see Finney (1971, Chapter 3.6) and Aitchison & Brown (1957, Chapter 1.2).
[src:logistic-regression/probit-model] A fast method for computing maximum likelihood estimates for the probit model was proposed by Ronald Fisher as an appendix to Bliss' work in 1935.
